Q. What Is a Record?

A record is a special kind of Java class introduced in Java 16 (after preview in Java 14/15) to represent
immutable data objects. Records are designed to reduce boilerplate code for classes whose main purpose is
to store data—like DTOs (Data Transfer Objects), value objects, or simple POJOs (Plain Old Java Objects)[1] [2].

Key Features:

1. Concise Syntax
Records use a compact syntax:

public record Person(String name, int age) {}

This single line creates:

(i)   Private, final fields for each component (name, age)
(ii)  A public constructor (Person(String name, int age))
(iii) Accessor methods (name(), age())
(iv)  equals(), hashCode(), and toString() methods


2. Immutability:
All fields in a record are final and private. Once a record object is created, its data cannot be changed.

3. Auto-generated Methods:
The compiler automatically generates:

-Accessor methods for each component (named after the component, not getX())
-equals() and hashCode() based on all components
-toString() that prints the record’s name and all components

4. Restrictions:

(i)   Records are implicitly final (cannot be extended)
(ii)  Records cannot have additional instance fields (only static fields/methods allowed)
(iii) Records extend java.lang.Record (cannot extend other classes)
(iv)  Records can implement interfaces
(v)   No-arg constructor is not allowed; only the canonical constructor (with all components) is generated


Customization:

1.Compact Constructor (Validation):

You can add validation logic in a compact constructor:

public record Range(int start, int end) {
    public Range {
        if (start > end) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Start cannot be greater than end");
        }
    }
}

2. Custom Canonical Constructor:

You can override the canonical constructor to modify or validate input:

public record Person(String name, int age) {
    public Person(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name.trim();
        this.age = age;
    }
}

3. Additional Constructors and Methods:

You can add extra constructors (must delegate to the canonical one), static fields, and methods:

public record Person(String name, int age) {
    public static final String UNKNOWN = "Unknown";

    public Person(String name) {
        this(name, 0);
    }

    public String nameInUpperCase() {
        return name.toUpperCase();
    }

    public static Person createUnknown(int age) {
        return new Person(UNKNOWN, age);
    }
}


Advanced Features:

a. Implementing Interfaces

Records can implement interfaces:

public interface Shape { double area(); }

public record Circle(double radius) implements Shape {
    @Override
    public double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}

b.Generic Records

Records can be generic:

public record Pair<T, U>(T first, U second) {}

c.Static Members

You can add static fields and methods:

public record Transaction(String id, double amount) {
    private static final String PREFIX = "TXN-";
    public static Transaction create(double amount) {
        return new Transaction(PREFIX + System.currentTimeMillis(), amount);
    }
}

Serialization:

Records that implement Serializable use the canonical constructor during deserialization,
ensuring immutability and validation logic are preserved. Custom readObject/writeObject methods are
ignored for records[1].

More detailed description:

Q. What are records ?

Java Records are a special kind of class introduced in Java 16 (after preview in Java 14/15) to model
immutable data objects in a concise way. They are ideal for data carriers like DTOs (Data Transfer Objects)
and value objects.

Q. Why Records?
Before records, you had to write a lot of boilerplate code for simple data classes:

(i)   Private final fields
(ii)  Constructor
(iii) Getters
(iv)  equals(), hashCode(), toString()

Records generate all of these automatically, making your code cleaner and less error-prone[1] [2].

2. Syntax and Auto-Generated Members

Basic Syntax:

public record Person(String name, int age) {}

This single line generates:

-Private final fields: name, age
-Public constructor: Person(String name, int age)
-Accessor methods: name(), age() (not getName()/getAge())
-equals(), hashCode(), toString() methods

Example

Person p = new Person("Alice", 30);
System.out.println(p.name()); // Alice
System.out.println(p); // Person[name=Alice, age=30]

3. Key Characteristics and Restrictions"

(i)  Immutability: All fields are final and private.
(ii) Implicitly final: Records cannot be extended (no inheritance).
(iii)Extends java.lang.Record: All records extend this abstract class.
(iv) No additional instance fields: You cannot add new instance variables in the body.
(v)  Can implement interfaces: Records can implement one or more interfaces.
(vi) No-arg constructor not allowed: Only the canonical constructor (with all fields) is generated[1] [2].


Basic definition:

Record basically helps you to create immutable class , with less boilerplate code . With just one line ,
all the basic syntax of fields , constructor , getter and setter are added to your code , implicitly .
From the arguments you pass in the record , they become the field of the respective immutable class .
(Don't use the keyword class, while writing the record) .